Choosing Variables:

  1. Independent Variable: OverallQual: Overall material and finish quality

  2. Dependent Variable: SalePrice - the propertys sale price in dollars. This is the target variable that youre trying to predict.

X = OverallQual

Y = Sales price

hist(sc.data$OverallQual)

# X = OverallQual
# Y = SalesPrice

X <- sc.data$OverallQual
Y <- sc.data$SalePrice

The chosen independent variable (OverallQual) has skewed data to the right. (A skewed right distribution is one in which the tail is on the right side. )

Probability:

Definitions of Probablities:

P(X=x and Y=y) = P(x,y)

If X and Y are independent then

P(x,y) = P(x) P(y)

P(x | y) is the probability of x given y

P(x | y) = P(x,y) / P(y)
P(x,y) = P(x | y) P(y)

If X and Y are independent then
P(x | y) = P(x)

a) P(X > x | Y > y)

Formula Conditional Probability (2 events): P(B|A) = P(A n B) / P(A)

P(X|Y) = P(Y n X) / P(Y)

# Count of Y (SalestPrice) greater than 129975
countofY <- sum(Y > y) 
countofY
## [1] 1095
# Count of X (OverallQual > 5.0)
countofX <- sum(X > x)
countofX
## [1] 922
# Count of both (Y > y and X > x)
countofBoth <- (sum(Y > y & X > x))
countofBoth
## [1] 848
# Probability

(countofBoth / length(X)) / (countofY / length(Y))
## [1] 0.7744292

b) P(X > x, Y > y)

# Count of both (X > x and Y > y)
countofBoth2 <- sum(X > x & Y > y)
countofBoth2
## [1] 848
# Probability

(countofBoth2 / length(X)) / (countofY / length(Y)) * (countofY / length(Y))
## [1] 0.5808219

c) P(X < x | Y > y)

# Probability

P(AB)=P(A)P(B) ?

ProbA <- sum(X > x)/length(X)
ProbA
## [1] 0.6315068
ProbB <- sum(Y > y)/length(Y)
ProbB
## [1] 0.75
ProbAnProbB <- ProbA * ProbB
ProbAnProbB
## [1] 0.4736301

P(AB)=P(B)P(A|B) Product Rule By Definition

Definitions

The conditional probability of A given B is the probability of event A, if event B

occurred. P(A|B)

A is independent of B if the conditional probability of A given B is the same as the

unconditional probability of A. P(A|B) = P(A), so we will use this test to determine

independence between variables.

#P(A|B) = P(A)
#P(X>x|Y>y) = P(X>x)

#P(X>x|Y>y)
(sum(Y > y & X > x) / length(X)) / (sum(Y > y) / length(Y))
## [1] 0.7744292
#P(X>x)
sum(X > x) / length(X)
## [1] 0.6315068

P(A|B) = 0.77 and P(A) = 0.63 are not equal,hence, the two variables are dependent. In addition, P(A|B) = 0.77 and ProbBnProbA = 0.47 are not equal.

Chi-Square

The Chi Square Test, tests the hypothesis of whether the Overall Quality is independent of the Sale Price.

tbl <- table(X > 5, Y > 129975)
tbl
##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   291  247
##   TRUE     74  848
chisq.test(tbl)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  tbl
## X-squared = 382.02, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

NULL Hypothesis: Overall Quality has no impact on Sale price

Alternative Hypothesis: Overall Quality has an impact on Sale price

We can reject the NULL Hypothesis given the p-value (< 2.2e-16) is less than 0.05.

Correlation Matrix for any 3 quantitative variables in dataset.

Pearson Correlation Test:

The Pearson correlation coefficient can take a range of values from +1 to -1. A value of 0 indicates that there is no association between the two variables. A value greater than 0 indicates a positive association.

# X = Overall Quality Y = Sale price Z = Year built
Z <- sc.data$YearBuilt
data <- data.frame(X, Y, Z)
cm <- cor(data)
cm
##           X         Y         Z
## X 1.0000000 0.7909816 0.5723228
## Y 0.7909816 1.0000000 0.5228973
## Z 0.5723228 0.5228973 1.0000000
# Correlation Test for Y and X
cor.test(Y, X, conf.level = 0.92)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Y and X
## t = 49.364, df = 1458, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 92 percent confidence interval:
##  0.7731789 0.8075387
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.7909816

Discussion:

We see above a Pearson correlation of 0.7910 between Y and X. There exists a positive association between Sales price and Overall quality. If overall quality goes down or up, it will affect the sale price.

T-Test Definition:

In statistics, Welchs t-test, or unequal variances t-test, is a two-sample location test which is used to test the hypothesis that two populations have equal means.

# Run the T test
t.test(Y, X, conf.level = 0.92)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Y and X
## t = 87.016, df = 1459, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 92 percent confidence interval:
##  177272.7 184557.5
## sample estimates:
##    mean of x    mean of y 
## 1.809212e+05 6.099315e+00

Discussion:

The T-Test shows difference in the means between Overall Quality and Sale Price. The difference in means is not equal to 0.

Definition of Familywise Error:

The familywise error rate (FWE or FWER) is the probability of a coming to at least one false conclusion in a series of hypothesis tests . In other words, its the probability of making at least one Type I Error. The term familywise error rate comes from family of tests, which is the technical definition for a series of tests on data.

A Type I error (sometimes called a Type 1 error), is the incorrect rejection of a true null hypothesis. The alpha symbol, alpha, is usually used to denote a Type I error.

Would you be worried about familywise error? Yes.

Why or why not? It is entirely possible that the first series of tests were affected by personal bias or just got lucky. Another set of tests should be done as well, with choosing the same variables and data. The second and third set of tests would be a validation step with different people performing the tests.

R3 = R3 -0.5723 x R1

R3 = 1.5168 * R3

\[A = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 &| 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0.3745 & 0.0702 &| -0.7909 & 1 & 0\\ 0 & 0 & 1 &| -0.6431 & -0.2844 & 1.5168 \end{pmatrix}\]

R2 = R2 -0.07020 * R3

#Rounded to 4 decimal places

\[A = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.7909 & 1.0000 & 0.5228 \\ 0.5723 & 0.5228 & 1.0000 \end{pmatrix}\]

Using Gaussian Elimination method

R2 = R2 - 0.079 x R1

\[A = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.7909 & 0.3743 & 0.0702 \\ 0.5723 & 0.5228 & 1.0000 \end{pmatrix}\]

R3 = R3 - 0.5723 x R1

\[A = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.0000 & 0.3743 & 0.0702 \\ 0.0000 & 0.0702 & 0.6724 \end{pmatrix}\]

R3 = R3 = 0.1875 x R2

\[A = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.0000 & 0.3743 & 0.0702 \\ 0.0000 & 0.0000 & 0.6593 \end{pmatrix}\]

Let U =

\[U = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.0000 & 0.3743 & 0.0702 \\ 0.0000 & 0.0000 & 0.6593 \end{pmatrix}\]

r #L consists of the multipliers used in the Gaussian elimination with 1s on the diagonal. \[L = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.0000 & 0.0000 \\ 0.7909 & 1.0000 & 0.0000 \\ 0.5723 & 0.1875 & 1.0000 \end{pmatrix}\]

Hence, A = LU \[ \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.7909 & 1.0000 & 0.5228 \\ 0.5723 & 0.5228 & 1.0000 \end{array} \right] = \begin{bmatrix} 1.0000 & 0.0000 & 0.0000 \\ 0.7909 & 1.0000 & 0.0000 \\ 0.5723 & 0.1875 & 1.0000\end{bmatrix} \times \left[ \begin{array}{c} 1.0000 & 0.7909 & 0.5723 \\ 0.0000 & 0.3743 & 0.0702 \\ 0.0000 & 0.0000 & 0.6593 \end{array} \right] \]

Calculus-Based Probability & Statistics.

#Get minimun value (Since, X has a minimum value of 1, I did not shift X)
min(X)
## [1] 1
#nonZeroMin <- min(X[X!=0])

#Shift the variable above 0

#shiftedX <- X + nonZeroMin

#Find the optimal value

lambda <- fitdistr(X, densfun = "exponential")$estimate["rate"]
lambda
##      rate 
## 0.1639528
#Take samples
exponential_distribution_of_X <- rexp(1000, lambda)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(X)
hist(exponential_distribution_of_X)

#Percentiles
percentiles5th95th <- quantile(exponential_distribution_of_X, c(0.05,0.95))
percentiles5th95th
##         5%        95% 
##  0.2181892 17.0787935
#Formula: normal distribution we calcualte the Confidence Interval as: CI = Sample Mean plus/minus standard error.

lower_left <- mean(X) - qnorm(0.95) * sd(X) / sqrt(length(X))
lower_left
## [1] 6.03978
upper_right <- mean(X) + qnorm(0.95) * sd(X) / sqrt(length(X))
upper_right
## [1] 6.15885
#Provide the empirical 5th percentile and 95th
quantile(X, c(0.05, 0.95))
##  5% 95% 
##   4   8

Definition:

Suppose p(x) is a density function for a quantity. The cumulative distribution function (cdf) for the quantity is de???ned as P(x) = integral from lower bound -infinity to upper bound x where p(t) dt. Gives: The proportion of population with value less than x The probability of having a value less than x.

https://www.quora.com/What-is-a-cumulative-distribution-function

Intuitive definition of CDF A CDF is a function that describes the probability of a random variable taking on a given value or less. A good example is rolling a single 6-sided die. Normally, we talk about the probability of a given number coming upfor example, the probability of rolling a 2 is 1 out of 6, 1/6, 0.166667. (That probability is described by the probability mass function, or PMF.) But what if you dont just want 2; you are okay with a 2 or any number less than it? In this case, there is only one other number: 1. So now when you roll your die, you are looking for a 2 OR a 1. You are now looking for 2 outcomes out of 6, so the probability is 2/6 = 1/3. Similarly, if you want a 3 or less, the probability is 3/6 or 1/2. Its called cumulative because you find the probability by adding up the individual probabilities of all the outcomes included. In the case of our die, when you want a 2 or less, you have 2 outcomes fulfilling this condition: 1 and 2, each with an individual probability of 1/6. 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 or 1/3, which is the cumulative probability of a 2. Thats what cumulative meansaddition.

Discussion:

The variable X (Overall quality) does not have any zeros, and so we did not shift the data. Next, we generated 1000 samples. Comparing the histograms of the original data (X) versus exponential distribution (exponential_distribution_of_X), we can see there is a difference. The exponential distribution reduced much of the right-skew; coming closer to a normal distribution.

The 5th and 95th percentiles using the cumulative distribution function of 1000 samples provided 0.3481007 and 18.5301051 respectively.

The 5th and 95th percentiles of the original data is 4 and 8 respectively.

The Residuals versus Fitted graph shows error Residuals versus fitted values. The dotted line at y = 0 indicates our fit line. Any point on the fit line has zero residual. Points above have positive residuals and points below have negative residuals.

The Normal Q-Q plot is close to a straight line. The closer the points are to falling directly on the diagonal line then the more we can interpret the residuals as normally distributed.

The Scale-Location Plot graph indicates the spread of points across predicted values range. One of the assumptions for Regression is Homoscedasticity . i.e variance should be reasonably equal across the predictor range. A horizontal red line is ideal and would indicate that residuals have uniform variance across the range. As residuals spread wider from each other the red spread line goes up.

Definitions:

Influence : The Influence of an observation can be thought of in terms of how much the predicted scores would change if the observation is excluded. Cooks Distance is a pretty good measure of influence of an observation.

Leverage : The leverage of an observation is based on how much the observations value on the predictor variable differs from the mean of the predictor variable. The more the leverage of an observation , the greater potential that point has in terms of influence.

The Residuals versus Levarage Plot

In this plot the dotted red lines are Cooks distance and the areas of interest for us are the ones outside dotted line on top right corner or bottom right corner. If any point falls in that region , we say that the observation has high leverage or potential for influencing our model is higher if we exclude that point.

The R-Squared is 93.32% This statistic indicates the percentage of the variance in the dependent variable that the independent variables explain collectively. R-squared measures the strength of the relationship between your model and the dependent variable on a convenient 0 - 100% scale.

0% represents a model that does not explain any of the variation in the response variable around its mean. The mean of the dependent variable predicts the dependent variable as well as the regression model.

100% represents a model that explains all of the variation in the response variable around its mean. Usually, the larger the R2, the better the regression model fits your observations.

So, in this instance, 91.92% is above 50%, which may indicate that the variables chosen above could be good indicators.

The Adjusted R-Squared is 91.92%. This value is slightly lower than R-Squared which adds evidence that the all predictors chosen do not necessarily improve the model. We may have to start eliminating variables to improve Adjusted R-Squared.

The P-value is less than 0.05.

Reference: http://r-statistics.co/Linear-Regression.html

How to know if the model is best fit for your data?

The most common metrics to look at while selecting the model are:

STATISTIC CRITERION

R-Squared Higher the better (> 0.70)

Adj R-Squared Higher the better

F-Statistic Higher the better

Std. Error Closer to zero the better

t-statistic Should be greater 1.96 for p-value to be less than 0.05

AIC Lower the better

BIC Lower the better

Mallows cp Should be close to the number of predictors in model

MAPE (Mean absolute percentage error) Lower the better

MSE (Mean squared error) Lower the better

Min_Max Accuracy => mean(min(actual, predicted)/max(actual, predicted)) Higher the better

#For the Fourth variation, we will narrow down the variables based on p-value and correlation test result value >0.50

#https://www.statisticssolutions.com/pearsons-correlation-coefficient/

#Perfect: If the value is near  1, then it said to be a perfect correlation: as one variable increases, the other variable tends to also increase (if positive) or decrease (if negative).
#High degree: If the coefficient value lies between  0.50 and  1, then it is said to be a strong correlation.
#Moderate degree: If the value lies between  0.30 and  0.49, then it is said to be a medium correlation.
#Low degree: When the value lies below + .29, then it is said to be a small correlation.
#No correlation: When the value is zero.

#Using only variables where the variable's p-value < 0.001 and correlation test value > 0.50

for (i in 2:length(sc.data)) {
  if(is.numeric(sc.data[,i])){
  a <- cor.test(sc.data$SalePrice, sc.data[,i])
  #print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " est:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  if (a$p.value < 0.001 && a$estimate > 0.50) {
    print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " cor:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  }  
  }
}

Justisfication for the Fourth variation to multiply the variables versus adding

Variables when added produce the following stats

Multiple R-squared: 0.7737, Adjusted R-squared: 0.7721

F-statistic: 495.4 on 10 and 1449 DF, p-value: < 2.2e-16

Compared to variables when multipled product the following stats

Multiple R-squared: 0.9662, Adjusted R-squared: 0.9268

F-statistic: 24.57 on 784 and 675 DF, p-value: < 2.2e-16

Discussion on 4th submission:

The multiple R-squared of 96.62 > 70%. The Adjusted R-squared is 92.68 and higher the better. The F-statistic is 24.57 and higher the better. The p-value < 0.05.

#For the variation model, we will narrow down the variables based on p-value and correlation test result value > 0.60

#https://www.statisticssolutions.com/pearsons-correlation-coefficient/

#Perfect: If the value is near  1, then it said to be a perfect correlation: as one variable increases, the other variable tends to also increase (if positive) or decrease (if negative).
#High degree: If the coefficient value lies between  0.50 and  1, then it is said to be a strong correlation.
#Moderate degree: If the value lies between  0.30 and  0.49, then it is said to be a medium correlation.
#Low degree: When the value lies below + .29, then it is said to be a small correlation.
#No correlation: When the value is zero.

#Using only variables where the variable's p-value < 0.001 and correlation test value > 0.60

for (i in 2:length(sc.data)) {
  if(is.numeric(sc.data[,i])){
  a <- cor.test(sc.data$SalePrice, sc.data[,i])
  #print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " est:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  if (a$p.value < 0.001 && a$estimate > 0.60) {
    print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " cor:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  }  
  }
}

#For the Sixth variation, we will narrow down the variables based on p-value and correlation test result value > 0.70

#https://www.statisticssolutions.com/pearsons-correlation-coefficient/

#Perfect: If the value is near  1, then it said to be a perfect correlation: as one variable increases, the other variable tends to also increase (if positive) or decrease (if negative).
#High degree: If the coefficient value lies between  0.50 and  1, then it is said to be a strong correlation.
#Moderate degree: If the value lies between  0.30 and  0.49, then it is said to be a medium correlation.
#Low degree: When the value lies below + .29, then it is said to be a small correlation.
#No correlation: When the value is zero.

#Using only variables where the variable's p-value < 0.001 and correlation test value > 0.70

for (i in 2:length(sc.data)) {
  if(is.numeric(sc.data[,i])){
  a <- cor.test(sc.data$SalePrice, sc.data[,i])
  #print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " est:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  if (a$p.value < 0.001 && a$estimate > 0.70) {
    print(paste(colnames(sc.data)[i], " cor:", a$estimate, " p=value:", a$p.value))
  }  
  }
}
